"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794300","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-01","<p>The Department does not record disabling conditions of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claimants at registration stage. Disabling conditions are recorded on the PIP Computer System only for those claimants who undergo a face to face or paper based assessment.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore we are unable to provide the number of refused PIP applications which were made by people with Myalgic Encephalomyelitis.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794300/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-01T10:07:58.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794300/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794300/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-23","Personal Independence Payment: Oxfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for Personal Independence Payments from people with Myalgic Encephalomyelitis have been rejected in (a) Oxford (b) Oxfordshire (c) Oxford West and Abingdon constituency in each of the last 5 years.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","115273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794301","Home Office","false","2017-12-04","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given to the Hon. Member for Hampstead and Kilburn on 2 December 2016, UIN 55490.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794301/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-04T17:18:56.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794301/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794301/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-23","Marriage Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress she has made on the implementation of her policy to  include mothers names on marriage certificates.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","115274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794302","Home Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Home Office has a number of officials who are working, or have worked, on proposals to include mothers’ names on marriage certificates. This work forms just part of these officials' wider responsibilities.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794302/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T17:22:11.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794302/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794302/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-23","Marriage Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many officials in her Departmental are working on (a) administrative, (c) technical and (c) legislative tasks relating proposals to include a mother's name and details on marriage certificates.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","115275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794303","Home Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>All marriage registrations in England and Wales are recorded on a computer system that is used by registration officers administrating the registration service. Changes would need to be made to this system to allow mothers names and details to be recorded. This can only be achieved once the necessary legislation is in place.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794303/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T17:32:38.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794303/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794303/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-23","Marriage Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, (a) how many and (b) which computer systems will need to be altered to allow mothers names and details to be given on marriage certificates.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","115276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794304","Home Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>Any change to the content of the marriage entry to include mothers’ names would ideally also bring forward reform to how marriages are registered to introduce efficiencies and create a more secure system for the maintenance of marriage records.</p><p> </p><p>To introduce such reform would require changes to primary legislation, in particular the Marriage Act 1949, and associated regulations. We continue to look for opportunities to introduce the legislative change required.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794304/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T17:27:58.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794304/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794304/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-23","Marriage Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which acts of Parliament need to be amended in order to allow mothers' names and details to be given on marriage certificates.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","115277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794305","Home Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>This information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794305/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T17:15:38.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794305/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794305/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-23","Biometric Residence Permits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department holds data on biometric resident permit cards that have required revision due to errors in England.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","115278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794306","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-28","<p>The government is working with industry to extend the benefits of discounted travel. My current expectation is that, after a trial period, this card will be subject to a binding agreement between all franchised operators.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794306/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T11:07:47.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794306/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794306/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-23","Railways: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the 26-30 year old travel discount scheme is mandatory for all Train Operating Companies.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","115279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794307","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Ordsall Chord connects Manchester’s three main railway stations for the first time. It will enable more trains to run to Piccadilly from the south and will support new and direct services across the region. By 2020, passengers as far afield as Newcastle and Bradford will benefit from faster, more frequent journeys to Manchester Airport as a result of this new link.</p><p> </p><p>The corridor that includes Manchester Piccadilly and Manchester Oxford Road will increase from 12 to 15 trains per hour from May 2018. This increase in capacity is not linked to the building of the Ordsall Chord, it is as a result of changing the rules about how the corridor will operate.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794307/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T16:18:10.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794307/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794307/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-23","Railways: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to ensure that Orsdall Chord of the Great North Rail Project delivers full capacity at (a) Manchester Piccadilly and (b) Manchester Oxford Road stations.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","115280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794308","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-28","<p>In each procurement a risk assessment is taken based on the project or services being delivered.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794308/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T16:08:38.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794308/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794308/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-23","Transport: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the ability of (a) Carillion and (b) Babcock to fulfil their contractual obligations in the transport sector.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","115281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794309","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Department has allocated a total budget of £80 million which, together with the Rail Delivery Group’s mobile barcode programme and the work of Transport for the North, will offer smart ticketing coverage to almost all of the country by the end of 2018.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794309/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T16:22:42.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794309/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794309/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-23","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the cost of the roll-out of smart ticketing and what the timetable is for that roll-out across the UK.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","115282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794310","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-01","<p>There are 66 fully operational speed enforcement cameras on the motorway network and a further 24 are in final stages of installation/commissioning as the Department continues the rollout of new installations as part of Smart Motorways.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of speed enforcement cameras on ‘A’ roads which form part of the Strategic Road Network is not held centrally and the data would need to be sought from each safety camera partnership.</p><p> </p><p>Cameras on other roads are a matter for each local highway authority and no estimate has been made of the total number of active safety cameras.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794310/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-01T14:41:21.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794310/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794310/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-23","Speed Limits: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of active road safety cameras.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","115283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794311","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>We estimate there are approximately 20,000 British citizens living in Zimbabwe, many of whom are long-term residents.</p><p>We ask all British nationals to regularly check travel advice.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794311/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T15:51:32.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794311/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794311/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-23","Zimbabwe: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent estimate has made of the number of British citizens living in Zimbabwe.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","115284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794312","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-04","<p>Exports of products from the UK’s 84 geographical indications (GIs) are valued at approximately £5bn per year, and about £1billion in domestic sales. Much of the production takes place in rural, often remote, areas providing vital input to local economies. This includes, for example, Scotch whisky and Scottish farmed salmon which are the UK’s two largest GI exports by value, and Welsh lamb, as well as smaller-scale products like Stornoway Black Pudding and Yorkshire Wensleydale cheese.</p><p> </p><p>GI protection acts in two ways to add value to rural economies. Firstly, it increases the value of the protected products. Academic studies suggest that UK consumers are prepared to pay between 7% and 20% more for GI products, though this varies considerably from product to product. Secondly, it protects sales volumes, particularly of exports, by preventing others from imitating the genuine article.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794312/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-04T11:53:21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794312/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794312/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-23","Food: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the value the 84 Protected Geographical Indicators add to the rural economy","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","115285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794313","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794313/answer","PQ115286.pdf","PQ115286.pdf","UKSA response","UKSA response",,"2017-11-28T16:11:57.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794313/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794313/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-23","Emigration: Zimbabwe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent estimate his Department has made of the size of the Zimbabwean diaspora in the UK.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","115286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794314","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-29","<p>Regulatory provisions for radioactive substances activities, including the accumulation and management of radioactive waste, are contained in Schedule 23 of the Environmental Permitting Regulations 2016.</p><p> </p><p>On 5 October the government published draft updates to Schedule 23 in “Consultation on Revised requirements for radiological protection: regulation of public exposures and the justification of practices”. The proposals are based on current scientific evidence, as reflected in the latest safety standards issued by the International Atomic Energy Agency and the requirements of the corresponding Euratom Basic Safety Standards Directive, which enters into force in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The public consultation closed on 15 November. Once the consultation responses have been considered, and subject to parliamentary timetables, updated regulations will be laid before this House in 2018.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794314/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-29T13:56:34.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794314/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794314/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-23","Radioactive Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to update the regulatory provisions governing nuclear waste in light of recent natural science evidence concerning the health effects of low-ionizing radiation.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","115287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794315","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-01","<p>At the 17 Conference of the Parties for CITES the UK contributed to achieving strong outcomes for tigers and other Asian big cats species.</p><p> </p><p>Since then Defra has funded a workshop which took place in Vietnam on 7 and 8 September 2017. The UK Border Force, along with the National Crime Agency and others held a training workshop with Vietnam’s border staff to share expertise in tackling wildlife crime at the borders including issues such as illegal shipment of animal parts and derivatives. The programme included best practice in training wildlife crime officers and setting wildlife crime priorities.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794315/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-01T12:29:12.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794315/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794315/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-23","Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department has taken to reflect Decision 17.225 of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) in the UK.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","115288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794316","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-01","<p>The Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976 was updated in 2007, following review and consultation. The Act was updated again in 2010 to allow local authorities to focus their enforcement activity more effectively. Based on available evidence we consider that the Act is currently providing appropriate protections.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794316/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-01T11:37:54.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794316/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794316/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-23","Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department has taken to review compliance with and enforcement of the Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","115289"
