"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793510","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-06","<p>Work conducted by the Government during the summer highlighted the risk posed to the social care sector as a consequence of historical liabilities associated with &quot;Sleep-in&quot; shifts. The Government is exploring options to minimise the impact on the social care sector, including holding discussions with the European Commission. On 1 November 2017, in recognition of the extraordinary circumstances affecting the social care sector, HMRC introduced the Social Care Compliance Scheme. This is an interim enforcement scheme designed to facilitate a solution to the issue of National Minimum Wage underpayment for sleep-in shifts in the social care sector.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793510/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T14:08:08.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793510/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793510/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-22","Social Services: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the cost to local authorities of the new requirement to comply with a social care providers scheme linked to payments for sleep-in care; and whether the new burdens doctrine will apply to such costs.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793511","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>No formal consultation took place ahead of the announcement of the Government’s scheme to fund termination of pregnancy services in England for women from Northern Ireland. However, there has been engagement with stakeholders throughout the development of our proposals including with officials from the Northern Ireland Executive.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793511/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:19:58.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793511/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793511/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, which (1) organisations, and (2) individuals, they consulted prior to making that statement; and whether those consultations took place with organisations and individuals that do not support abortion.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793512","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>The provision of funded termination of pregnancy services in England for women from Northern Ireland does not change the position in relation to the provision of abortions in Northern Ireland, which is a matter for the Northern Ireland Executive and the Northern Ireland Assembly. Our proposals do not include the provision of any services in Northern Ireland.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793512/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:17:44.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793512/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793512/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, what assessment they have made of the impact of the extension of that support on the process of devolution to Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793513","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>The Government remains neutral on changes to abortion legislation.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793513/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:18:07.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793513/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793513/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, whether their policy on abortion is (1) neutral, (2) in support, or (3) against.","false","Biography information for Lord Browne of Belmont",,"Lord Browne of Belmont","HL3480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793515","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-30","<p>The Small Business Commissioner will consider complaints about payment issues between small business suppliers (with fewer than 50 staff) and their larger customers, making non-binding recommendations. A complaint will be considered by the Small Business Commissioner if it relates to a payment matter which could be a request or other act, or a failure to pay or other omission in relation to payment.</p>",,"Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793515/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T15:58:34.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793515/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793515/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-22","Small Business Commissioner","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the Small Business Commissioner is able to intervene where service suppliers demand payment in less than 30 days from the date of the invoice.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL3481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793516","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-04","<p>Local planning authorities are required to determine planning applications for development in accordance with their Local Plan, national policy and other material considerations.</p><p>The temporary national permitted development right for the change of use of light industrial buildings to residential use requires the building to have been in light industrial use on 19 March 2014, and if not in use on that date for light industry to have been the last use. There are no requirements in respect of how long the building must have been in that use. The right does not apply to buildings whose use for light industrial use commenced after 19 March 2014.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793516/answer",,,,,"HL3483","2017-12-04T14:55:36.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793516/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793516/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-22","Change of Use","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government for how long buildings and workshops with planning permission for light industrial use must be (1) in existence, and (2) used for such purposes, before they may be converted for residential use.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL3482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793517","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-04","<p>Local planning authorities are required to determine planning applications for development in accordance with their Local Plan, national policy and other material considerations.</p><p>The temporary national permitted development right for the change of use of light industrial buildings to residential use requires the building to have been in light industrial use on 19 March 2014, and if not in use on that date for light industry to have been the last use. There are no requirements in respect of how long the building must have been in that use. The right does not apply to buildings whose use for light industrial use commenced after 19 March 2014.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793517/answer",,,,,"HL3482","2017-12-04T14:55:36.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793517/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793517/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-22","Change of Use","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to issue planning authorities with guidance on whether applications for permission to construct light industrial buildings or workshops should be considered in the light of the possibility of a later application for change of use to residential purposes.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL3483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793518","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-04","<p>Taxi and private hire vehicle (PHV) services must be accessible to those who rely upon them, and disability awareness training can be effective in equipping drivers with the skills and knowledge to provide all passengers with the assistance they require. The Department is currently considering the responses to the consultation on the draft Accessibility Action Plan which will inform the updated Best Practice Guidance for taxi and PHV licensing authorities.</p><p> </p><p>It is the Department’s expectation that the guidance will include a recommendation that authorities should use their existing powers to require prospective drivers to complete disability awareness and equality training. There are however no existing powers to give this guidance statutory status.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, my Right Honourable Friend, the Minister of State for Transport, announced in a Westminster Hall debate that he would be setting up a working group to consider current issues concerning taxi and PHV licensing such as this and it will be reporting its findings in the New Year.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793518/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-04T13:44:25.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793518/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793518/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-22","Taxis: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to implement the recommendation, made by the Select Committee on the Equality Act 2010 and Disability (Session 2015–16), to ensure that no taxi driver or private hire vehicle driver is licensed without having undertaken disability equality training; and whether they have any plans to introduce statutory guidance to that end.","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL3484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793520","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>Local authorities are responsible for the design of their public spaces and have a duty to take account of the needs of disabled people. The Government is absolutely clear that the needs of the whole community should be considered when councils are looking to introduce any public realm scheme, including shared space.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport has been working with the Chartered Institution of Highways and Transportation (CIHT) on its review of shared space and other street design schemes. The review has considered a wide range of issues regarding shared space, and we expect CIHT’s report to make recommendations for further work, including in relation to current guidance. The Government will respond to those recommendations in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793520/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T12:38:02.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793520/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793520/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-22","Shared Spaces: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure that shared space schemes address the needs of disabled people; and whether they intend to commit, in the Department for Transport Accessibility Action Plan, to update the 2011 Local Transport Note, as recommended by the Select Committee on the Equality Act 2010 and Disability (Session 2015–16).","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL3485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793521","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Government’s consultation on the draft transport Accessibility Action Plan closed on Wednesday 22nd November. The final version will be published in 2018 and will set out the Government’s ambitions in this area based on the feedback provided. The final Plan will also set out the Government’s timescale for delivery.</p><p><br>The Government remains committed to introducing an Accessible Information Requirement, expanding the provision of audible and visible information to local bus services across Great Britain, so helping passengers to travel with greater confidence.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793521/answer",,,,,"HL3488","2017-12-04T13:44:52.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793521/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793521/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-22","Bus Services: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan, in the Department for Transport Accessibility Action Plan, to confirm timescales for the publication of the Accessible Information Requirement regulations associated with the Bus Services Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL3486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793522","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Government is committed to delivering a transport system which works for all. The draft Accessibility Action Plan (AAP) was published in August for a three month consultation. The consultation is now closed and the Government is analysing the responses received.</p><p> </p><p>The final AAP will be published in 2018 and will set out the Government’s ambitions for this agenda based on the feedback provided. The final Plan will also set out the Government’s timescales for delivery.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793522/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-04T13:41:14.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793522/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793522/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-22","Public Transport: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they will take to ensure that the desired outcomes set out in the Department for Transport Accessibility Action Plan will be achieved within the timescales set out in the document.","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL3487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793523","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Government’s consultation on the draft transport Accessibility Action Plan closed on Wednesday 22nd November. The final version will be published in 2018 and will set out the Government’s ambitions in this area based on the feedback provided. The final Plan will also set out the Government’s timescale for delivery.</p><p><br>The Government remains committed to introducing an Accessible Information Requirement, expanding the provision of audible and visible information to local bus services across Great Britain, so helping passengers to travel with greater confidence.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793523/answer",,,,,"HL3486","2017-12-04T13:44:52.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793523/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793523/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-22","Bus Services: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure that the updated version of the Department for Transport Accessibility Action Plan addresses the recommendations of the Select Committee on the Equality Act 2010 and Disability (Session 2015–16) regarding audio-visual announcements on buses.","false","Biography information for Baroness Deech",,"Baroness Deech","HL3488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793525","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-05","<p>The Government recognises the need to review the Memorandum of Understanding with the devolved administrations. The decision to review the Memorandum of Understanding must be taken with the agreement of the four participating administrations - the UK Government, Scottish Government, Welsh Government and Northern Ireland Executive.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793525/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-05T11:57:32.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793525/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793525/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Devolution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to update the Memorandum of Understanding with the devolved administrations, published in October 2013, in order to take account of relevant issues affecting devolution which have arisen in the last four years.","false","Biography information for Lord Elystan-Morgan",,"Lord Elystan-Morgan","HL3489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793526","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-05","<p>The UK Governance Group brings together under one command the Cabinet Office Constitution Group, the Scotland Office, the Office of the Advocate General for Scotland and the Wales Office. This Group leads the UK Government’s work on constitutional and devolution issues, and is the primary source of advice to UK Government Ministers and Departments for this area.</p><p>Activities and performance of the Group are reported in the Cabinet Office annual report and the annual reports of the other departmental constituent parts of the Group.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793526/answer",,,,,"HL3491","2017-12-05T12:00:20.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793526/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793526/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","UK Governance Group","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to publish regular reports of the meetings of the UK Governance Group established in June 2015 to lead work on constitutional and devolution issues.","false","Biography information for Lord Elystan-Morgan",,"Lord Elystan-Morgan","HL3490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793527","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-05","<p>The UK Governance Group brings together under one command the Cabinet Office Constitution Group, the Scotland Office, the Office of the Advocate General for Scotland and the Wales Office. This Group leads the UK Government’s work on constitutional and devolution issues, and is the primary source of advice to UK Government Ministers and Departments for this area.</p><p>Activities and performance of the Group are reported in the Cabinet Office annual report and the annual reports of the other departmental constituent parts of the Group.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793527/answer",,,,,"HL3490","2017-12-05T12:00:20.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793527/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793527/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","UK Governance Group","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how often the UK Governance Group has met in 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Elystan-Morgan",,"Lord Elystan-Morgan","HL3491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793528","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-05","<p>The UK Government has been clear that the devolved administrations should be fully engaged in preparations for the UK’s exit from the EU. The Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations facilitates engagement and collaboration on EU Exit. In addition to the formal structures of the Joint Ministerial Committee, constructive bilateral engagement with the devolved administrations on a wide range of policy areas related to EU Exit continues at both Ministerial and official level.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793528/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-05T12:02:56.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793528/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793528/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Devolution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the undertaking given in paragraph 20 of the October 2013 Memorandum of Understanding that they would “involve the devolved administrations as fully as possible in discussions about the formulation of the UK’s policy position on all EU and international issues which touch on devolved matters”, whether they plan to involve Scottish and Welsh Ministers directly in decision-making concerning such discussions.","false","Biography information for Lord Elystan-Morgan",,"Lord Elystan-Morgan","HL3492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793529","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-05","<p>The Government is continuing discussions with the devolved administrations, working through the relevant areas of EU law to determine where common approaches will and will not be required, and the different forms that common approaches could take. The common framework principles agreed at the Joint Ministerial Committee (European Negotiations) are guiding these discussions. The Government expects that the return of powers from the EU will lead to a significant increase in the decision making powers for the devolved administrations.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793529/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-05T12:01:22.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793529/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793529/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the UK Governance Group has taken a view on which legislative powers currently vested in the EU should be transferred to Wales or Scotland on departure from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Elystan-Morgan",,"Lord Elystan-Morgan","HL3493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793531","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-05","<p>The UK will continue to work with the UN to develop its plans for Syria following a national settlement of the conflict. However, we will provide no support for reconstruction until a comprehensive, genuine and inclusive political transition is firmly underway.</p><p>While the conflict is ongoing, our priority is to deliver life-saving humanitarian aid. DFID-funded partners are providing support in north-east Syria including to Kobane and Jazira.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793531/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-05T13:46:34.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793531/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793531/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-22","Syria: Reconstruction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 21 November (HL3104), on what grounds they are withholding reconstruction aid from the Jazira and Kobane cantons of northern Syria pending a comprehensive political transition, given that they have been freed from Daesh and that schools, hospitals and private homes have suffered damage.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793532","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-07","<p>Our High Commission to Canberra most recently discussed the issue with the Australian Department for Foreign Affairs and Trade in November 2017. We also raised this at the UN Human Rights Council Universal Periodic Review of Australia in November 2015.​</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793532/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-07T15:45:36.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793532/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793532/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-22","Australia: Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions, whether through Commonwealth channels or otherwise, they have had regarding the achievement of humane improvements in the current treatment of refugees and asylum applicants seeking to enter Australia.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793533","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-07","<p>The UK Government keeps its list of proscribed organisations under constant review. The EU reviews its CT Sanctions Regime every six months. The UK Government currently has no plans to remove the proscription of the Kurdistan People's Party (PKK).</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793533/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-07T15:49:53.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793533/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793533/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-22","PKK","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether (1) they, and (2) the EU, intend to review their decisions to classify the Kurdistan People’s Party as a terrorist organisation, following the decision of the Belgian Court of Appeal on 14 September that that organisation is a party to an armed conflict.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL3496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793534","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-07","<p>The UK is deeply concerned by the humanitarian situation and calls for all parties to immediately provide unhindered commercial and humanitarian access. The Prime Minister met with the Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia during her visit to Riyadh on 29 November and was clear on the importance of a resolution to the conflict and humanitarian and commercial access to all of Yemen. The Foreign Secretary raised the urgency of the humanitarian situation with the Crown Prince on 23 November and has also spoken with the Secretary-General of the UN.</p><p>On 22 November, the Saudi-led Coalition announced that they would allow humanitarian flights and shipments to resume. We welcome progress towards reopening the ports in Hodeidah, Salif and Sana'a airport. A small number of humanitarian and commercial vessels have been able to berth at these ports. To prevent a humanitarian catastrophe, more needs to be done and quickly. The UK will continue pressing at the very highest levels for complete and unhindered commercial and humanitarian access to all of Yemen.</p><p>The UK Government takes its arms export licensing responsibilities very seriously and operates one of the most robust arms export control regimes in the world. All export licence applications are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking account of all relevant factors at the time of the application.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793534/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-07T15:46:41.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793534/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793534/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-22","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the statement made by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 20 November (HL Deb, col 46), what actions they are taking within the UN to ensure that action is taken to allow the immediate provision of supplies to Yemen; what representations they have made to the government of Saudi Arabia regarding ending their blockade of Yemen; whether a timescale has been established for such action to be taken; and whether, given the UK's alliance with Saudi Arabia, they have any plans to review licences for arms supplies to that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Lea of Crondall",,"Lord Lea of Crondall","HL3497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793536","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Minister for Africa visited Kasai Central, in the DRC, in November 2017 to see for himself the impact of the conflict. UK bilateral aid is already supporting 25,800 children with food assistance in the Kasais. Over the next 5 years the UK will be providing a range of humanitarian support. As part of this, we will support a further 840,000 people nationally with food assistance, including people in the Kasais.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793536/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-04T15:42:00.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793536/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793536/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-22","Democratic Republic of Congo: Food Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what humanitarian assistance they are giving to support those suffering from starvation in the Kasai region of Congo.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL3498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793537","Department of Health","false","2017-12-01","<p>The chronic fatigue syndrome/myalgic encephalomyelitis (CFS/ME) National Outcome Database was developed by three NHS Clinical Network Co-ordinating Centres in 2006 and managed by Bristol University. Its development was part of a wider initiative to establish services for CFS/ME in the National Health Service at the time. Neither the Department nor NHS England has oversight of it, or responsibility for it.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793537/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-01T11:43:26.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793537/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793537/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Chronic Fatigue Syndrome","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when the Chronic Fatigue Syndrome/Myalgic Encephalomyelitis National Outcomes Database ceased to exist; and why the data included in that database is no longer collected.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL3499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793538","Department of Health","false","2017-12-05","<p>The World Health Organization’s Global Advisory Committee on Vaccine Safety publishes a summary outcome of its vaccine safety reviews on a six-monthly basis. The outcome of the Committee’s most recent review of human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine safety was published on 14 July 2017. A copy of the <em>Weekly epidemiological record</em> is attached, which summarises the latest six month review. This review found no new adverse events of concern for HPV vaccine based on many very large, high quality studies.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793538/answer","GACVS 14 Jul 2017.pdf","GACVS 14 Jul 2017.pdf","Weekly epidemiological record","Weekly epidemiological record",,"2017-12-05T11:55:14.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793538/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793538/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to place a copy of the systematic review of serious adverse reactions following HPV vaccines, commissioned by the World Health Organisation, in the Library of the House.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL3500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793539","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The department has no direct knowledge of the study entitled <em>‘</em><em>Unidentified Chronic Fatigue Syndrome/myalgic encephalomyelitis is a major cause of school absence: surveillance outcomes from school-based clinics’</em>, published by the British Medical Journal in 2011 or any activity undertaken by schools in connection with this study.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793539/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T17:26:02.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793539/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793539/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-22","Pupils: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether parental consent was obtained by school attendance officers before parents were sent letters by researchers for the study entitled Unidentified Chronic Fatigue Syndrome/myalgic encephalomyelitis is a major cause of school absence: surveillance outcomes from school-based clinics, published by the British Medical Journal in 2011.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL3501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793541","Department of Health","false","2017-12-06","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has evaluated the following glucose monitors used by people living with diabetes:</p><p> </p><p>- Integrated sensor-augmented pump therapy systems for managing blood glucose levels in type 1 diabetes (the MiniMed Paradigm Veo system and the Vibe and G4 PLATINUM CGM system). NICE has evaluated these products through its diagnostics programme. The MiniMed Paradigm Veo system is recommended as an option for managing blood glucose levels in people with type 1 diabetes only if they have episodes of disabling hypoglycaemia despite optimal management with continuous subcutaneous insulin infusion.</p><p> </p><p>- MiniMed 640G system with SmartGuard for managing blood glucose levels in people with type 1 diabetes. This is a NICE advice product, developed under its Medtech innovation briefings (MIBs) programme. MIBs provide a summary of the best available evidence for selected new technologies and are designed to assist National Health Service planning and decision-making. MIBs are not designed to include treatment advice but provide a critical review of the strengths and weaknesses of the relevant evidence, therefore NICE do not make any recommendations for (or against) funding the device.</p><p> </p><p>- FreeStyle Libre for glucose monitoring, which measures interstitial fluid glucose levels in people with diabetes. This is also a Medtech innovation briefing therefore NICE do not make any recommendations for funding the device.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Regional Medicines Optimisation Committee (North), one of four Committees established by NHS England to provide advice to the NHS, reviewed the use of the Freestyle Libre at its meeting on 26 October 2017. In developing its advice, the Committee took into account the MIB published by NICE. The Committee has issued guidance on the use of Freestyle Libre suggesting a careful start to its use and data collection to better understand the benefits. Freestyle Libre has been approved for reimbursement on NHS prescription from 1 November through listing in Part IX of the Drug Tariff.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>NICE does not have a role in proactively monitoring the delivery of local services, so it has not made any assessment of decisions taken by some clinical commissioning groups not to fund these technologies.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793541/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T13:29:52.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793541/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793541/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Diabetes: Medical Equipment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence has undertaken any evaluation of glucose monitors used by people living with diabetes; if so, whether such monitors are approved for use; and what assessment they have made of the decision taken by some Clinical Commissioning Groups not to prescribe such monitors to diabetes patients.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL3502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793542","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>723 women from Northern Ireland accessed abortions in England in 2016. Our planning has considered estimates that range from 1,000 to 2,000 women seeking access to services in England in each of the next three years.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793542/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:37:14.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793542/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793542/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, what is their estimate of the number of women who will travel from Northern Ireland to England to seek an abortion in the current and each of the next three financial years.","false","Biography information for Lord Morrow",,"Lord Morrow","HL3503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793543","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>Marie Stopes International (MSI) are continuing to take a range of actions to address the issues identified in the Care Quality Commission’s (CQC) reports. The CQC re-inspected MSI earlier this year and have made clear that they will not hesitate to take further action, if necessary, in order to guarantee MSI meets the standard of care they expect and that its patients deserve.</p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to monitor the situation with particular regard being had to the statutory approval responsibilities of the Secretary of State.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793543/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:26:22.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793543/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793543/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, what assessment they have made of the finding in the report by the Care Quality Commission, published in December 2016, that several clinics operated by Marie Stopes International were in serious breach of safety guidelines; and what steps they will take to ensure that women attending those clinics receive safe abortions.","false","Biography information for Lord Morrow",,"Lord Morrow","HL3504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793544","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>Following the inspection, a joint action plan between the Care Quality Commission (CQC), BPAS Merseyside, and Halton Clinical Commissioning Group was formulated to ensure all issues raised during the inspection were fully addressed. The CQC is monitoring the action plan through ongoing engagement with BPAS Merseyside. Overall, the CQC has found that improvements continue to be made at BPAS Merseyside both from a clinical and a governance perspective.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793544/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:32:37.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793544/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793544/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, what assessment they have made of the finding in the report by the Care Quality Commission, published in January, that the Merseyside Clinic operated by the British Pregnancy Advisory Service was in breach of a number of safety guidelines; and what steps they will take to ensure that women attending that clinic receive safe abortions.","false","Biography information for Lord Morrow",,"Lord Morrow","HL3505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793545","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>To participate in the scheme providers must be registered with the Care Quality Commission (CQC) and, in the case of independent sector providers, be approved by the Secretary of State to perform abortions. There are no requirements in place based on CQC ratings.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793545/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:29:32.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793545/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793545/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, whether women receiving such support will be required to attend an abortion clinic achieving a particular rating by the Care Quality Commission; and if so, what that rating will be.","false","Biography information for Lord Morrow",,"Lord Morrow","HL3506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793546","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>If an overnight stay is deemed to be clinically necessary, those who meet the financial hardship criteria will have suitable accommodation booked for them.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793546/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:27:23.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793546/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793546/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, including support with travel costs for those meeting financial hardship criteria, whether that support will include the costs of accommodation.","false","Biography information for Lord Morrow",,"Lord Morrow","HL3507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793548","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>We have developed criteria similar to that used in the National Health Service low income scheme. To receive support for travel costs women must be in receipt of benefit, such as universal credit, jobseeker’s allowance or income support or have an income of £15,276 a year or less.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793548/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T17:27:54.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793548/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793548/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 October (HLWS190) announcing further support for women from Northern Ireland seeking an abortion in England, including support with travel costs for those meeting financial hardship criteria, what those criteria will be.","false","Biography information for Lord Morrow",,"Lord Morrow","HL3508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793549","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK and Canada are already close allies. We work closely on defence and intelligence matters and enjoy close cooperation on many issues where we have commons aims and values. We are the only two countries that are members of all four of The Commonwealth, NATO, the G7, and the G20.</p><p><br>The Prime Minister visited Ottawa on 18 September, to strengthen ties between the UK and Canada. During her visit, a new framework for cooperation was agreed, a new Strategic Dialogue involving our Foreign, Defence and Development Secretaries will be supported by a Public Policy Forum.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793549/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T15:28:42.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793549/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793549/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-22","Canada: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to improve political relations with the government of Canada.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL3509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793550","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-28","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer I gave to Lord West of Spithead on 25 September 2017, to Question number HL1505. There are currently no plans to review the decision to decommission HMS OCEAN in 2018.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793550/answer","Hansard Extract 25 September 2017, HL1505.docx","Hansard Extract 25 September 2017, HL1505.docx","HL1505 - WQnA extract on HMS OCEAN","HL1505 - WQnA extract on HMS OCEAN",,"2017-11-28T17:16:40.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793550/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793550/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-22","HMS Ocean","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to review the sale of HMS Ocean, in the light of that ship's role in providing support to the Overseas Territories hit by hurricanes this summer.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL3510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793551","Department for International Trade","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK Government is committed to seeking to ensure continuity in its current trade and investment relationships as we leave the European Union, including those covered by free trade agreements such as the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA).</p><p>On 18 September, the Prime Minister and PM Trudeau announced that both would work together to ensure a seamless transition of agreements such as CETA into new bilateral arrangements.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793551/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T11:35:10.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793551/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793551/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-22","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the future involvement of the UK in the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement between the government of Canada and the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL3511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793553","Home Office","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Home Office has received a small number of letters from members of the public about Operation Conifer.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793553/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T13:12:46.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793553/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793553/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-22","Edward Heath","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 7 November (HL2758), whether they have any evidence of public concern caused by Operation Conifer, which was undertaken by Wiltshire Police.","false","Biography information for Lord Sherbourne of Didsbury",,"Lord Sherbourne of Didsbury","HL3512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793554","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The adult education budget funds learners aged 19 and over. It is not allocated by age group or qualification type and through freedoms and flexibilities providers can earn their allocation in line with the funding rules we set each year.</p><p> </p><p>Information on volumes of full level 2 and 3 qualifications can be found in table 3 of the further education and skills: November 2017 main table which is attached and also available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/further-education-and-skills-november-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/further-education-and-skills-november-2017</a>. Please note that this includes Offenders<strong>’</strong> Learning and Skills Service provision and shows all level 2 and 3 qualifications not just first full level 2 and 3 qualifications.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793554/answer","HL3513 attachment.xlsx","HL3513 attachment.xlsx","Information on volumes of full level 2 and 3","Information on volumes of full level 2 and 3",,"2017-12-06T17:33:36.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793554/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793554/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-22","Adult Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much of the adult education budget in England in 2016–17 was allocated to 16–24 year olds (1) in total, (2) for those on first full Level 2 courses, and (3) for those on first full Level 3 courses.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Clifton",,"Lord Smith of Clifton","HL3513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793555","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Resource Accounting and Budgeting (RAB) charge for fee loans for part-time higher education undergraduate students is estimated to be around 40%.</p><p>The RAB charge for Advanced Learner Loans at Level 3 is estimated to be around 50%-55%. The estimate includes Access to Higher Education (HE) courses which allow any learner progressing to HE to have their loan written off at the point of completing their HE course.</p><p>The RAB charge for Advanced Learner Loans at Level 4 and above is estimated to be around 20%-25%.</p><p>It is estimated that the RAB charge for part-time higher education undergraduate loans will increase to around 45% once maintenance loans have been made available to part-time students.</p><p> </p><p>The cost of the system is a conscious investment in young people. It is the policy subsidy required to make higher and further education widely available, achieving the government’s objectives of increasing the skills in the economy and ensuring access to university for all with the potential to benefit.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793555/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T16:32:26.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793555/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793555/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-22","Students: Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the resource accounting budgeting charge in England for (1) fee-loans for part-time higher education undergraduate students, (2) loans for adult learners at Level 3, (3) loans for adult learners at Levels 4 and 5, and (4) future maintenance loans for part-time higher education undergraduate students.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Clifton",,"Lord Smith of Clifton","HL3514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793556","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-06","<p>The United Kingdom believes that Taiwan has a valuable contribution to make on global issues such as the Sustainable Development Goals</p><p>The UK's longstanding policy on Taiwan remains the same. The UK supports Taiwanese membership of international organisations where statehood is not a pre-requisite for membership. In situations where Taiwanese membership of international organisations is not possible, we welcome pragmatic solutions that allow Taiwan to contribute to the global good, such as Taiwan's voluntary efforts to support the UN's 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793556/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-06T15:35:23.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793556/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793556/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-22","Taiwan: Sustainable Development","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to support the participation of Taiwan in the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL3515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793891","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>The discretionary payments for the remainder of this financial year will not change and there will be no reductions. NHS Business Services Authority is carrying out a review of the discretionary payment arrangements and the new system will be launched in April 2018. The new discretionary payment scheme will be a fairer, more transparent and flexible system that will direct funding to those most in need of financial support. As under the existing arrangements this discretionary support will be open to all beneficiaries, including bereaved partners of the infected and their families. There will also be an increase in the overall level of discretionary funding for 2018-19 as announced in September 2017.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793891/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T12:40:19.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793891/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793891/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the oral Question of the hon. Member for Weaver Vale and the response from the Under-Secretary of State on 14 November, HC Deb, Vol. 631, Col. 143, whether that commitment applies to all ongoing payments currently received by the bereaved partners of those infected.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","114980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793892","Department of Health","false","2017-11-30","<p>Delivery of Cost Improvement Programmes will be a major part of helping any trust to deliver its control totals. Circumstances will vary across trusts and NHS Improvement will offer a range of support packages for trusts facing gaps in their financial targets and these are tailored to trusts’ needs appropriately. The National Health Service leadership bodies have developed their own plan in partnership with local providers to deliver financial sustainability in this and future years.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793892/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T12:22:35.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793892/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793892/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-22","Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust will be required to take in the event that it is unable to accrue those savings required by the current cost improvement programme.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","114981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793893","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-01","<p>The Behavioural Insights Team (BIT) was spun out of government in 2014 and set up as a social purpose company.</p><p> </p><p>We are not in a position to provide information about the proprietary assets of Behavioural Insights Team Limited, due to commercial confidentiality.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793893/answer",,,,,,"2017-12-01T14:31:08.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793893/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793893/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what data the Behavioural Insights Team holds on those people it can reach with its Predicitiv product; how many such people there; and what the origin of that data is.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","114982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793894","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-30","<p>The Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea (RBKC) has committed to provide survivors from Grenfell Tower and Grenfell Walk with a permanent new home in social housing within one year of the fire. We are working closely with RBKC to support them to deliver this commitment, and receive regular updates on rehousing progress, which we continue to monitor carefully.</p><p>Following the fire, the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government set up the independent Grenfell Recovery Taskforce to provide assurance that RBKC has the capacity and capability to deliver an effective long term recovery plan for its residents, taking into account their views. In his statement to the House on 6 November, the Secretary of State echoed the conclusion of the Taskforce’s first report that the pace of delivery by RBKC was too slow and needed significant improvement. I expect the Council to do whatever is necessary to ensure households can move into settled homes as swiftly as possible. It is important that the rehousing proceeds at a pace which respects the needs, wants and situations of survivors but we have been equally clear that bureaucratic inertia must not add delay.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793894/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T16:23:07.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793894/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793894/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-22","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the timetable for the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea to rehouse Grenfell Tower households in permanent accommodation; what assessment he has made of the capacity of that local authority to meet that timetable; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","114983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793895","Home Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>The dedicated Grenfell immigration policy is a targeted scheme that we expect to benefit a limited number of people.</p><p> </p><p>We have plans to publish statistics on the Grenfell immigration policy in due course and will not be providing updates on numbers in the meantime.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793895/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T17:56:34.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793895/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793895/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-22","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Grenfell Tower fire survivors have been granted (a) limited leave to remain in the UK and (b) permanent residence.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","114984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793897","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-30","<p>The UK has had regular contact with the Zimbabwean Government over the last two weeks. Most recently, I met with incoming President Emmerson Mnangagwa on Friday. Officials have also met Chief of Defence Staff General Chiwenga.</p><p>These dramatic political events were clearly triggered by a military intervention. But the most important thing now is that Zimbabweans are able to exercise their constitutional right to elect a civilian government. This can only happen through free and fair elections. A re-establishment of a civilian-led government with a clear separation between the party and the state must be a priority. The UK has made this clear to the Government of Zimbabwe.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793897/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-30T16:32:43.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793897/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793897/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-22","Zimbabwe: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to the Government of Zimbabwe on ensuring the monitoring of the activities of the Zimbabwean Defence Force and their return to barracks.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","114986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793898","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-27","<p>Government has recently consulted on whether improvements could be made to the existing restructuring options available within the insolvency regime. A summary of responses to this consultation was published in September 2016. Government has continued to discuss the proposals with interested parties and the issues that they raised since this time. This further engagement will ensure that any reforms, if necessary, will be fit for purpose and best achieve the Government’s aims of rescuing distressed but viable businesses, therefore preserving both value and jobs.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793898/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-27T11:41:37.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793898/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793898/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-22","Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy if he will bring forward legislative proposals to facilitate the restructuring at an early stage of viable businesses in order to prevent their insolvency and any adverse consequential effects on other firms and jobs in the supply chain.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","114987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793899","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-18","<p>Following developments within the Sheffield City Region Combined Authority, in particular some constituent members signalling that they no longer support the deal, the Government believes that the most sensible approach is to pause our work on the innovation pilot. This, we hope, will give further time for local issues to be considered and resolved, giving greater clarity on the future of the partnership and the extent of continuing local support for the pilot from all constituent members of the Combined Authority.</p><p> </p><p>Despite taking the decision to pause this work, the Government remains fully committed to the Sheffield City Region devolution deal. Our main ambition is to work collaboratively to realise all elements of the devolution deal and to deliver the innovation pilot as soon as possible, once all partners have been able to recommit to the agreement.</p><p> </p><p>We will keep this situation under close review with the hope that work on the innovation pilot can continue at the earliest viable opportunity.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793899/answer",,,,,"114874","2017-12-18T17:53:21.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793899/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793899/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-22","Employment Schemes: Sheffield City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect on the level of unemployment in the Sheffield City Region of the Government's decision to pause the Early Integrated Employment Support pilot.","false","Biography information for Jared O'Mara","Sheffield, Hallam","Jared O'Mara","114988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793900","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>UK public procurement policy is to award contracts on the basis of value for money, which means the optimum combination of cost and quality over the lifetime of the project. Wider socio-economic criteria can be taken into account at tender evaluation stage if they relate directly to the subject matter of a contract from the point of view of the contracting authority.</p><p> </p><p>The Public Contracts Regulations 2015 explicitly allows past performance to be taken into account, and we issued Procurement Policy Note 04/15 to assist public procurers to do so.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793900/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T16:04:40.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793900/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793900/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the effect of the provisions of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 set at in Procurement Policy Note 04/15 on restricting the taking into account of past performance in awarding contracts on competition, social value and value for money from the public purse.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","114989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793901","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>Following the election, Cabinet Office asked departments to update their Single Departmental Plans. The Government intends to reflect updated SDPs on GOV.UK later this year.</p><p> </p><p>In updated plans, departments have been asked to outline how planned activity will support the delivery of the Sustainable Development Goals.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793901/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-28T15:56:02.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793901/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793901/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Government Departments: Business Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what guidance he gives to government departments on the (a) timetable for publication of their Single Departmental Plans and (b) extent of content reference in those plans to steps to attain the Sustainable Development Goals; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","114990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793902","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-29","<p>The government will be implementing a track and trace scheme for tobacco products in line with our existing obligations and the timetable set out in the Tobacco Products Directive and the World Health Organisation Framework Convention on Tobacco Control Illicit Trade Protocol. The government is not aware of any EU plans for a licensing scheme for the tobacco market.</p><p> </p><p>The government has worked on the draft implementing legislation for the relevant parts of the Directive with the Commission and other Member States to try to ensure that, in line with better regulation principles, the system adopted is effective, efficient and proportionate in tackling the trade in illicit tobacco products which puts public health at risk and avoids the payment of duty. The government is not yet in a position to provide an assessment of the economic impact of the system. However, as a tool to help tackle the illicit market, the scheme will have a positive impact on the economy and public finances.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793902/answer",,,,,"114992 ; 114993 ; 114994","2017-11-29T16:45:35.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793902/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793902/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-22","Tobacco: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the Government's position is on implementing an EU licensing scheme for the tobacco market; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114991"
